Cyclistic Inc. Marketing Campaign

Bike_sharing service membership

Title: Bike sharing service memberships

Introduction:

The Bike Share service is a significant innovation in a world that is increasingly conscious of carbon emissions. Cyclistic Inc, a Bike-share company based in Chicago, USA, has successfully launched a bike-share service comprising a fleet of 5,824 bicycles locked in 692 stations. These bicycles are equipped with geo-tracking technology and can be unlocked at one station and used until they are returned to another station at any time.

There are basically two customer types in Cyclystic, the annual subscribers which are called members and the single ride or full-day pass users considered casual riders.

The stakeholders at Cyclistic are currently engaged in a marketing campaign and firmly believe that the company’s future success hinges on maximizing the number of annual memberships. For this project, I made the decision to utilize the R programming language due to the substantial size of the dataset. In addition, I employed Tableau for enhanced visualization capabilities and Excel to handle smaller excerpts of dataframes.

Buissiness Task:

As data analysts within the marketing team, our objective is to examine the distinct usage patterns of casual riders and annual members of Cyclistic bikes. Through these insights, we aim to develop a new marketing strategy utilizing digital media. Our focus is on converting casual riders, who are already acquainted with the Cyclistic bike-share, into annual members, rather than targeting entirely new customers.

This project follows the Ask,Prepare,Process,Analyze,Share, and Act phases of data analytics

Ask:

  • In what ways do subscription types, members, and casual riders utilize bikes differently?
  • What factors could motivate casual riders to purchase a membership?
  • How can Cyclistic Inc. leverage digital media to persuade casual riders to transition into members?

Deliverable: A set of data-backed recommendations on how the marketing team can utilize digital media to influence casual riders to transition to a membership.

It is evident from the analysis that there is a higher number of trips made by members compared to casual riders. Cyclistic Inc. currently serves a larger customer base of members, but it is important to note that the number of casual riders is still significant.

– Observe the duration of rides: Member Vs Casual–

Based on the data analysis, it is apparent that casual riders tend to take longer rides compared to users with membership cards, despite annual members being more frequent users. This observation leads us to infer that casual users might consider transitioning to membership if they are enticed by potential cost savings on longer trips that come with switching to a membership. By highlighting the financial benefits and emphasizing how membership can lead to significant savings on extended rides, Cyclistic Inc. could potentially encourage casual riders to convert into members.

Preferred Bike type by users: Which bikes do users prefer?

Electric and classic bikes are the most preferred type of bikes, while docked bike seems to be the least preferred by users.

– Preferred Bike type by members and casual riders

The visualization indicated that only a small fraction of casual riders uses docked bike, the preference for classic bikes and electric bike is confirmed in both casual and member users.

Monthly Ride By Type – We should observe monthly ride trends and how they differ between members and casual users

The plotted data reveals a noticeable trend where trips experience a substantial increase starting from March, coinciding with the onset of spring, and gradually decrease by October. The months of May through September stand out as having the highest ride numbers for both casual and member subscribers, indicating a significant surge in activity during the summer season.

– Observed in detail the difference in average ride length between members and casual users

The analysis reveals a notable disparity in average ride lengths between casual riders and members. Casual rides consistently exhibit considerably higher durations compared to members. This finding presents an opportunity to explore when attempting to convert casual riders into members. Notably, even at the start of the peak period in March, casual rides already exceed 14 minutes on average, a duration that members never reach throughout the entire series. Highlighting the potential cost savings on these longer rides by switching to membership could be a persuasive factor in encouraging casual riders to transition to become members.

Share and Act

Observations

  • While there are more member trips than casual trips, casual riders tend to take longer trips.

  • Analysis of weekday trends reveals that members primarily use bike trips during weekdays, likely for work or school purposes. In contrast, weekends show a higher proportion of casual riders, suggesting their rides are more recreational.

  • Hourly trends further support the hypothesis that member riders are likely students or workers, with sharp increases in the morning (commuting to work or school) and evenings (returning).

  • Monthly trends strongly indicate that bike usage increases during the warmer months, specifically from March to September. Additionally, while member trips have a moderate average ride duration, casual rides experience a sharp increase in duration from March onwards, with considerably higher durations than members.

  • We have identified the most popular start stations based on the analysis.

Recommendations

Recommendations to encourage casual users to switch to annual memberships:

  1. Enhance Membership Attractiveness:

    *Offer competitive prices for annual memberships, emphasizing the cost savings compared to casual rides, especially for longer trips.

    *Adjust pricing structure for casual rides to be more duration-dependent, incentivizing frequent users to opt for memberships.

  2. Target Specific Segments in Digital Campaign:

    *Focus the digital campaign message on workers and students, highlighting the convenience and financial benefits of membership for their daily commuting needs.

    *Emphasize significant cost savings on longer trips through membership, appealing to casual riders who frequently take extended rides.

  3. Time the Digital Campaign Strategically:

    *Launch the digital campaign around March, just as bike trips are expected to increase during the spring and summer seasons.

    *Target campaign banners and promotions at stations popular among casual riders, such as Kingsbury St & Kinzie St and Clark St & Elm Street, to effectively reach the intended audience.
